<head>ADULT</head>
    <list type="altnames">
<item>MATURE</item>
<item>GROWN-UP</item>
<item>FULLY GROWN</item>
<item>FULL-GROWN</item>
<item>FULLY DEVELOPED</item>
<item>OF AGE</item>
<item>OF LEGAL AGE</item>
    </list>
    <list type="translations">
        <item xml:lang="zh">成人</item>
    </list>
<div type="definition">
<p>HUMAN who is SUFFICIENTLY OLD to ESTABLISH his/her SEPARATE HOME.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>[GENERAL/SPECIFIC]</p>
<p>[GENERAL-USE/TECHNICAL]</p>
<p>[INFORMAL/OFFICIAL]</p>
<p>1. The current word for an adult is zhuàng 壯.</p>
<p>[GENERAL], [GENERAL-USE]</p>
<p>2. Dīng 丁 is an administrative term for a person fully capable of physical work, current from Qín times.</p>
<p>[OFFICIAL], [SPECIFIC], [TECHNICAL]</p>
<p>3. Guàn zhě 冠者 refers to a person above the age of 18, when the capping ceremony took place.</p>
<p>[ELEVATED], [GENERAL-USE]</p>
        </div>
<div type="modern-chinese-criteria">
<p>成年人</p>
<p>壯年人</p>
<p>壯夫</p>
<p>大人</p>
<p>人</p>
<p>丁</p>
<p>丁口</p>
<p>壯丁</p>
<p>丁壯</p>
<p>丁夫</p>
<p>丁男</p>
<p>丁女</p>
<p>全丁</p>
<p>佬 (rare) refers to an adult male.</p>
<p>rough draft to BEGIN TO identify synonym group members for analysis, based on CL etc. 18.11.2003. CH ／</p>
